WEBVTT

00:00.000 --> 00:16.240
What if I told you that the concept of progress, you know, and the evolution of life, and the steady march of scientific discovery, and even in the, like, the biological engineering of your own body, is a complete mathematically provable illusion?

00:17.760 --> 00:24.220
Welcome to the deep dive. Today, we are basically taking a sledgehammer to how you view reality.

00:24.220 --> 00:40.960
Yeah, it is quite the paradigm shift, honestly. I mean, we spend our entire lives deeply comforted by this idea of trajectories. We really want to believe that the universe, or, well, at least our little corner of it, is optimizing towards something better.

00:40.960 --> 00:50.900
Right. It's that invisible ladder we all think we're climbing. You look at a biology textbook, and the history of life on Earth feels like this relentless story of improvement, right?

00:50.980 --> 00:51.200
Yeah.

00:51.200 --> 01:20.820
From single-celled organisms all the way up to, and you look at an intricate organ, like the human eye, and it seems so perfectly, meticulously engineered for a really specific job. And then you look at human knowledge, the whole history of science, and it feels like a steady, cumulative mountain climb toward absolute objective truth. We love this narrative. We need things to have a purpose, I think. We want to be aimed at a goal.

01:20.820 --> 01:34.980
Which is exactly why the material we are dissecting today is so beautifully disruptive. Because when you truly examine the mathematics of how physical systems persist over time, that comforting ladder entirely vanishes.

01:35.420 --> 01:35.520
Wow.

01:35.740 --> 01:46.640
The universe isn't a sculptor slowly chipping away at a block of marble to reveal perfection. It is, mathematically speaking, just a giant, mindless sieve.

01:46.640 --> 01:57.620
Okay, let's unpack this, because we are getting into some profoundly mind-bending territory today. Our grounding text for this deep dive is a wildly fascinating independent research pager.

01:57.780 --> 01:58.540
It really is.

01:58.540 --> 02:08.340
It's titled, Selection Without Design, Constraint, Projection, and the Geometry of the Unseen. Written by an author who goes by the name...

02:08.340 --> 02:27.100
Our mission today is to take those three deeply held narratives you just mentioned, that evolution is an optimizer, that our biological systems have an intrinsic functional purpose, and that our knowledge is converging on absolute truth, and will completely deconstruct them.

02:27.100 --> 02:29.600
Break them right down to the studs.

02:29.660 --> 02:38.280
Exactly. And then, we are going to rebuild them from the ground up, using Fluxium's framework of dynamical systems and mathematical constraints.

02:38.520 --> 02:44.640
But before we jump into the deep end, I want to establish a really crucial baseline for you listening right now.

02:44.640 --> 02:53.680
Now, this paper isn't some cynical exercise in nihilism. We aren't sitting here saying nothing matters, or nothing is real.

02:53.820 --> 02:55.580
Right, it's not just pure skepticism.

02:55.700 --> 03:10.160
Far from it. This is about attempting to see the underlying mechanics of existence. The paper describes it as the geometry of the unseen. It's an exploration of the invisible constraints that dictate everything we are and everything we can ever know.

03:10.160 --> 03:12.280
So it's more about the hidden rules of the game.

03:12.280 --> 03:33.020
Yeah. If you could visualize the space we are entering today, don't picture a biology lab or a telescope. Picture a stark, vast, abstract, geometric arena filled with interlocking, multidimensional paths and rigid, unbreakable boundaries.

03:33.220 --> 03:34.200
That sounds intense.

03:34.200 --> 03:39.540
That is a phase space. That is the true arena of a dynamical system.

03:40.040 --> 03:51.760
I love that visual. A giant, dark room full of invisible tripwires. Let's actually start right there at the biological level and look at the tripwires of natural selection.

03:52.480 --> 04:00.120
If you open any standard high school biology textbook, the story of evolution is basically pitched to us as an engineering problem.

04:00.260 --> 04:01.600
It's always an engineering problem.

04:01.600 --> 04:14.960
Always. The classic metaphor we are taught is the fitness landscape. Imagine a massive 3D topographical map where the towering peaks represent high evolutionary fitness and the deep valleys represent low fitness.

04:15.720 --> 04:23.140
We are taught that populations of animals are constantly climbing these mountains, guided by the invisible hand of natural selection toward the summit.

04:23.140 --> 04:24.620
Which implies an active guide.

04:24.620 --> 04:34.520
Right. Mother nature is basically looking at a menu of genetic mutations and saying, ah, yes, thicker fur is objectively better for this wolf. Let's optimize for that.

04:35.060 --> 04:43.460
The fitness landscape is probably one of the most successful yet deeply misleading metaphors in the entire history of science.

04:43.960 --> 04:47.040
Flyxion completely dismantles it right out of the gate.

04:47.040 --> 04:49.740
So how does the paper take it down?

04:49.740 --> 04:56.840
The core argument of the paper is that natural selection does not optimize. At all. It simply filters.

04:57.640 --> 05:04.680
To understand the difference, we have to look at what is mathematically required to have an actual optimization process.

05:04.760 --> 05:05.860
Okay. Lay it on me.

05:05.980 --> 05:10.380
You need three distinct things. First, you need a space of possibilities.

05:10.380 --> 05:20.680
Second, you need an objective function. This is a mathematical rule that assigns a value or a score to every single state in that space.

05:20.820 --> 05:21.900
Like a grading rubric.

05:22.080 --> 05:23.440
Exactly like a rubric.

05:23.840 --> 05:31.840
And third, you need a directed search mechanism, something that actively pulls or steers the system toward the states with the highest scores.

05:31.840 --> 05:49.460
Right. Like a GPS routing algorithm. It knows the ultimate goal, you know, getting me to the grocery store. It scores all the possible street routes based on time and traffic. And then it actively directs me down the route with the best score.

05:49.620 --> 05:57.480
That is a perfect example of an optimizer. Natural selection, however, lacks the second and third components.

05:57.480 --> 05:57.900
Huh?

05:58.120 --> 06:03.140
There is no biological objective function and there is no directed search mechanism.

06:03.380 --> 06:03.920
None at all.

06:04.100 --> 06:18.120
None. The variations that arise in biology through random genetic mutation, chromosomal recombination, or just, you know, developmental noise, they are not guided by the fitness landscape.

06:18.920 --> 06:21.900
A wolf doesn't mutate thicker fur because it's cold.

06:22.180 --> 06:23.800
The mutations are just blind.

06:23.960 --> 06:25.600
Entirely blind to the environment.

06:25.600 --> 06:35.140
Selection then enters the picture, but it doesn't steer the wolf toward a peak. It merely applies a boundary condition. It says, well, if you freeze to death, you are excluded.

06:35.560 --> 06:37.040
Exclusion. That's the sieve.

06:37.220 --> 06:38.500
That is the sieve.

06:38.960 --> 06:44.000
Organisms that fail to survive and reproduce just don't contribute to the next generation.

06:44.340 --> 06:49.580
That does not mean the ones that survived were optimized. It strictly means they weren't destroyed.

06:49.880 --> 06:53.400
Let me try an analogy here to see if I'm really wrapping my head around this.

06:53.540 --> 06:53.740
Yeah.

06:53.740 --> 07:02.520
Imagine a massive, chaotic game show. You have a thousand contestants running around a giant arena in pitch blackness.

07:02.600 --> 07:04.240
Okay. I like where this is going.

07:04.440 --> 07:15.380
And the floor is randomly dropping out. Just massive trap doors opening up everywhere without warning, shifting based on completely random external factors.

07:15.380 --> 07:20.700
The people left standing at the end of the game, the people left standing at the end of the game aren't the best dancers.

07:21.000 --> 07:21.400
No.

07:21.400 --> 07:25.080
They aren't the smartest trivia players. They aren't the fastest runners.

07:25.080 --> 07:34.000
They're literally just the people who happened to be standing on a solid piece of floor when the surrounding pieces fell away.

07:34.000 --> 07:37.520
They literally just didn't fall through a hole.

07:37.520 --> 07:41.640
I think we need to push that analogy even further to really capture the math.

07:41.780 --> 07:43.660
It's not just that the floor is dropping.

07:44.220 --> 07:51.980
It's that the contestants themselves are constantly mutating, changing their shapes, tying their shoelaces together, or randomly jumping.

07:52.040 --> 07:55.160
Right. They're mutating blindly while the floor drops.

07:55.160 --> 08:03.400
Yes. If a contestant blindly stumbles to the left just as the trap door opens on the right, they survive.

08:04.280 --> 08:11.760
To look at that surviving player, who might be a terrible runner with tied shoelaces, and declare,

08:12.300 --> 08:22.720
this player is the optimal human for this game, requires you to project a narrative of progress that the game itself absolutely does not possess.

08:22.860 --> 08:24.800
The game doesn't care about their shoelaces.

08:24.800 --> 08:27.440
The game only cares that they didn't fall.

08:27.880 --> 08:33.940
Because the game doesn't have a scoring system. It only has an eliminated or not eliminated binary.

08:34.260 --> 08:41.620
Which brings us to the formal mathematical structure of persistence that Flyxion introduces. It's called the closure condition.

08:41.840 --> 08:44.120
The closure condition. Okay, let's break that down.

08:44.240 --> 08:49.400
In dynamical systems theory, you define a set of states. Let's call that set S.

08:49.400 --> 08:56.420
For that set to persist through time, it simply has to map into itself indefinitely under the rules of the system.

08:56.720 --> 08:57.540
Map into itself.

08:57.660 --> 09:05.320
Yeah. In mathematical notation, T of S, the transformation of the state over time, must remain a subset of S.

09:05.320 --> 09:09.780
So, the states just keep producing new states that are still inside the safe zone.

09:09.920 --> 09:10.140
Yeah.

09:10.240 --> 09:13.120
Like, the players keep stepping on floorboards that haven't dropped.

09:13.340 --> 09:18.140
Yes. It is just a dynamic loop that avoids breaking.

09:18.140 --> 09:30.400
The paper introduces two rigorous mathematical lemmas here to separate this idea of persistence from our very human obsession with optimality.

09:30.560 --> 09:31.140
What are lemmas?

09:31.260 --> 09:33.280
Let's look at lemma 2.5.

09:33.280 --> 09:43.440
It proves that just because a system persists, there is absolutely no guarantee it is moving toward a higher score on any metric you could possibly invent.

09:43.840 --> 09:48.600
So, it could be getting worse by our standards, but still surviving?

09:48.880 --> 09:59.140
Exactly. As long as it doesn't cross the boundary of destruction, a system can actually drift from states you might consider better or fitter to states you consider worse.

09:59.140 --> 10:04.140
Because there's no force pulling it up the mountain. It's just wandering aimlessly on the plateau.

10:04.580 --> 10:10.860
And then lemma 2.6 proves the flip side, which is even more devastating to the optimization narrative.

10:11.380 --> 10:21.980
It proves that you can have a state that perfectly, flawlessly maximizes your objective function, the absolute best possible state of biological fitness you could ever imagine.

10:22.180 --> 10:25.260
Like the ultimate, perfectly evolved organism.

10:25.260 --> 10:39.900
Right. But, if the dynamics of the system don't map that state back into itself, if, in the very next time step, it steps outside the boundary of the safe zone, it is instantaneously destroyed.

10:40.460 --> 10:43.020
Oh, wow. So, perfection can be fatal.

10:43.700 --> 10:48.700
Optimality does not guarantee persistence, and persistence does not equal optimality.

10:48.960 --> 10:53.420
They are mathematically orthogonal concepts. They have nothing to do with each other.

10:53.420 --> 11:07.940
But, hold on. I remember taking evolutionary biology in college, and there are incredibly complex mathematical equations that professors use to prove that populations do, in fact, optimize over time.

11:08.260 --> 11:10.220
The classic defenses of progress.

11:10.360 --> 11:15.780
Yeah. People always bring up the Price equation, or Ronald Fisher's Fundamental Theorem of Natural Selection.

11:15.960 --> 11:19.000
These are foundational pillars of mathematical biology.

11:19.600 --> 11:23.120
Does Fluxium just, you know, ignore a century of science?

11:23.120 --> 11:30.680
Not at all. Fluxium tackles them head-on to demonstrate how we, as a scientific community, have structurally misinterpreted them.

11:30.980 --> 11:34.480
Okay, let's take the Price equation first. How is that misinterpreted?

11:34.660 --> 11:45.900
Well, George Price developed this in the 1970s, and it is a breathtakingly brilliant, exact mathematical description of evolutionary change from one generation to the next.

11:45.900 --> 11:51.520
But Fluxium points out a glaring philosophical blind spot in how it's taught.

11:52.040 --> 11:58.540
The Price equation relies on measuring the covariance between a specific treat and fitness.

11:59.400 --> 12:06.700
Covariance. Okay, for those of us who haven't taken statistics recently, covariance is just how two things change together, right?

12:07.040 --> 12:09.940
Like, the taller you are, the higher you can reach in an apple tree.

12:10.540 --> 12:12.340
Height and apple-gathering coverage.

12:12.340 --> 12:14.600
That's a very intuitive way to grasp it.

12:14.820 --> 12:21.960
The Price equation measures how a trait changes based on its local, instantaneous correlation with reproductive success.

12:22.080 --> 12:23.600
Local and instantaneous.

12:23.820 --> 12:26.800
Plus any transmission biases, like mutation.

12:27.560 --> 12:29.360
But here is the critical catch.

12:30.040 --> 12:33.100
It is purely a local accounting mechanism.

12:33.780 --> 12:40.660
It has absolutely no reference to an external standard against which a trait is being optimized globally.

12:40.660 --> 12:46.540
I see. It only tells you what happened in that single momentary transition between yesterday and today.

12:46.800 --> 12:48.960
So it's a photograph, not a feature film.

12:49.160 --> 12:50.400
That's a great way to put it.

12:50.660 --> 12:53.320
It's just a snapshot of the sieve at work.

12:53.840 --> 13:01.400
It tells you which traits happen to be correlated with not falling through the trap door in that specific round of the game.

13:01.780 --> 13:09.440
It does not imply a global teleological trajectory towards some independent ideal of improvement.

13:09.440 --> 13:12.280
Okay, what about Fisher's Fundamental Theorem?

13:13.000 --> 13:16.180
That one literally has the word fundamental in it.

13:16.420 --> 13:18.000
That sounds pretty definitive.

13:18.640 --> 13:20.900
Fisher's Theorem is equally misunderstood.

13:21.800 --> 13:31.120
It asserts that the rate of increase in the mean fitness of any organism at any time is equal to its genetic variance in fitness at that time.

13:31.580 --> 13:34.600
And people read that and think, well, fitness is always going up.

13:34.600 --> 13:40.520
Exactly. Decades of biologists have read that and thought, aha, mean fitness is always increasing.

13:41.060 --> 13:43.280
Evolution is an engine of optimization.

13:44.440 --> 13:47.400
But Flyxion points out the fine print.

13:47.900 --> 13:49.220
There's always fine print.

13:49.660 --> 13:55.840
The theorem only applies to the additive genetic variance in fitness holding the environment completely static.

13:56.100 --> 13:58.520
But the environment is never static. Ever.

13:58.520 --> 14:09.760
Never. The moment the population evolves, the moment the climate shifts slightly, the moment a predator adapts or a prey species gets slightly faster, the entire landscape deforms.

14:10.080 --> 14:11.240
So the mountain moves.

14:11.740 --> 14:21.620
Fisher's Theorem is describing a local momentary tendency on a landscape that is constantly melting and reforming beneath the organism's feet.

14:21.620 --> 14:31.800
Right. You aren't climbing a mountain to the top. You are just desperately trying to keep your head above the water in a chaotic, churning ocean.

14:32.240 --> 14:34.900
There is no global optimum to reach.

14:35.000 --> 14:35.480
Exactly.

14:35.720 --> 14:48.120
Okay, so if we aren't being optimized, right, if we are truly just the lucky, stumbling contestants who didn't fall through the trapdoors, why do biological systems look so breathtakingly designed?

14:48.400 --> 14:50.720
The illusion of design is very powerful.

14:50.720 --> 14:58.180
It is. Why does the human eye have a lens of people and a retina that work in perfect mechanical harmony?

14:58.880 --> 15:04.300
Why do cellular enzymes perfectly lock into their substrates like a key in a vault?

15:04.940 --> 15:07.020
I mean, it screams design.

15:07.400 --> 15:12.640
It feels cognitively impossible to accept that this is just the result of a blind sieve.

15:12.760 --> 15:15.880
Which naturally leads us to question the origin of that illusion.

15:15.880 --> 15:23.820
To answer your question about the eye and the enzyme, we have to unpack a statistical concept that Flyxion calls conditional inflation.

15:24.040 --> 15:26.060
Conditional inflation. Let's break that down.

15:26.060 --> 15:33.520
Imagine setting up a mathematical probability space of all the possible chemical trajectories that could have occurred on earlier.

15:34.220 --> 15:46.960
We're talking about trillions of random molecular interactions, bubbling in hydrothermal vents and tide pools, happening every single second over millions of years.

15:46.960 --> 15:49.280
A massive soup of possibilities.

15:49.420 --> 15:55.040
The vast, overwhelming majority of those chemical trajectories lead absolutely nowhere.

15:55.380 --> 16:00.540
They fizzle out. They degrade into inert sludge. They fail to form anything stable.

16:00.540 --> 16:09.160
We, standing here today, only observe the infinitesimally tiny fraction of trajectories that did not terminate.

16:09.500 --> 16:21.700
Because our very existence as conscious observers depends entirely on being the end product of a persistent system, we are sampling from a highly filtered, maximally biased data set.

16:21.960 --> 16:27.440
Survivor bias. We are the survivors, looking backward through a multi-billion-year-old filter.

16:27.440 --> 16:32.960
Precisely. Flyxion formally states this as Proposition 3.1.

16:33.860 --> 16:46.120
If the strict constraints required to survive the chemical and biological sieve happen to correlate with things like mechanical complexity or metabolic efficiency or finely tuned enzymes,

16:46.480 --> 16:52.080
then when we look back, we will see a universe positively brimming with complexity and efficiency.

16:52.460 --> 16:55.140
Because all the simple, fragile stuff died.

16:55.140 --> 16:59.700
Exactly. We then make a massive, deeply flawed, logical leap.

17:00.100 --> 17:07.160
We falsely assume that the generative process, the universe itself, was actively aiming to produce that complexity.

17:07.420 --> 17:11.280
Oh, man. It's like looking at incredibly successful startup founders.

17:11.700 --> 17:17.300
You read their autobiographies or you watch their TED Talk, and they weave this perfect linear story of genius.

17:17.300 --> 17:25.840
First, I optimized my code, then I strategically pivoted my market fit, and it was all a brilliant, deliberate design from day one.

17:25.940 --> 17:26.720
They always say that.

17:26.900 --> 17:33.880
Right. But if you actually look at the data of early-stage venture capital, most of it was just throwing spaghetti at the wall.

17:33.880 --> 17:38.440
They were just trying desperately not to run out of money before the end of the month.

17:38.560 --> 17:40.920
They didn't perfectly design the company.

17:41.160 --> 17:47.220
They just accidentally stumbled into a configuration that didn't go bankrupt during a market crash.

17:47.360 --> 17:49.360
That is a phenomenal analogy.

17:49.360 --> 18:03.000
And then, because they survived, we put them on magazine covers, we look at their specific traits, you know, waking up at 4 a.m., drinking green juice, micromanaging their staff,

18:03.140 --> 18:08.120
and we assume those traits are the universal objective formula for optimization.

18:08.120 --> 18:19.060
We completely ignore the graveyard of 10,000 other founders who also woke up at 4 a.m. and drank green juice, but hit a bad market constraint and vanished.

18:19.060 --> 18:23.680
That is a perfect example of conditional inflation in human behavior.

18:24.300 --> 18:29.640
We inflate the conditional expectation of success based purely on the traits of the survivors,

18:30.300 --> 18:35.320
and Flyxion applies this exact same rigorous logic to the origin of life itself.

18:35.520 --> 18:35.860
How so.

18:35.860 --> 18:47.140
The text forces us to abandon the romantic idea that life began with a heroic, optimized discovery of some magical, self-replicating DNA molecule.

18:47.880 --> 18:51.920
The origin of life was, frankly, a sloppy chemical accident.

18:51.920 --> 18:58.900
I love that phrase, a sloppy chemical accident, like a wobbly, mismatched IKEA table held together by duct tape.

18:59.060 --> 19:02.800
And we're assuming a master carpenter spent 10 years designing it.

19:03.180 --> 19:05.680
Explain the actual biology of this accident.

19:05.860 --> 19:13.840
Flyxion leans on the work of theoretical biologist Stuart Kaufman here, specifically his concept of autocatalytic sets.

19:14.200 --> 19:15.100
Autocatalytic sets.

19:15.380 --> 19:21.960
The idea is that you do not need a perfectly optimized, high-fidelity replicator to kickstart life.

19:22.100 --> 19:28.120
You just need a messy network of chemical reactions that achieve what Flyxion terms mutual admissibility.

19:28.340 --> 19:29.320
Mutual admissibility.

19:29.320 --> 19:31.200
So they just allow each other to exist.

19:31.320 --> 19:31.800
Exactly.

19:32.140 --> 19:39.320
Molecule A accidentally helps catalyze the creation of molecule B. Molecule B happens to help create molecule C.

19:39.900 --> 19:42.780
And molecule C just so happens to catalyze molecule A.

19:42.780 --> 19:43.460
On a closed loop.

19:43.660 --> 19:44.620
A closed loop.

19:45.100 --> 19:47.500
Now, none of these molecules are optimizing anything.

19:48.080 --> 19:50.160
The cycle might be incredibly inefficient.

19:50.700 --> 19:52.620
It might be energetically wasteful.

19:52.620 --> 19:55.460
It might leak resources constantly.

19:55.960 --> 19:58.240
But it satisfies the closure condition.

19:59.200 --> 20:01.140
T-gas is a subset of S.

20:01.600 --> 20:04.920
You're hitting on the exact mathematical core of the paper.

20:05.800 --> 20:17.920
They collectively catalyze their own production just enough to not get destroyed by the temperature or the pH levels or the UV radiation of their surrounding environment.

20:18.120 --> 20:20.060
They just found a safe corner to hide in.

20:20.060 --> 20:24.160
They blindly stepped into the admissible region of the dynamical system.

20:24.460 --> 20:27.940
And because their structure formed a loop, they simply stayed there.

20:28.260 --> 20:30.860
So life didn't begin because it was good at anything.

20:31.060 --> 20:34.960
It began because it just managed to not fail the exclusion criteria.

20:35.180 --> 20:35.560
Right.

20:35.820 --> 20:36.460
But wait.

20:37.060 --> 20:42.840
As we look at the fossil record, we do see organisms getting more complex.

20:43.460 --> 20:44.380
Brains get bigger.

20:44.820 --> 20:46.340
Nervous systems get more intricate.

20:46.340 --> 20:49.960
Does that mean optimization kicks in later in the game?

20:50.060 --> 20:52.360
It is so tempting to think so.

20:52.480 --> 20:53.000
But no.

20:53.660 --> 21:00.780
It just means that more complex networks don't exist because they are better in some absolute objective sense.

21:00.780 --> 21:08.900
They exist because a wider, more complex web of interconnected reactions is simply harder to break.

21:09.260 --> 21:09.400
Oh.

21:10.340 --> 21:13.380
It's about robustness, not optimization.

21:13.380 --> 21:13.860
Yes.

21:13.860 --> 21:23.380
If you have a simple chemical cycle with only three steps and the temperature of the pond drops slightly, the cycle might break and banish forever.

21:23.700 --> 21:24.640
It's too fragile.

21:24.640 --> 21:34.640
But if you have a massively complex cycle with three million interlocking steps, redundant pathways, and feedback loops, it can absorb more environmental shocks.

21:35.140 --> 21:39.600
It maintains its admissibility across a much wider range of chaotic conditions.

21:39.600 --> 21:42.900
So the complex systems aren't climbing higher on a mountain.

21:43.060 --> 21:46.320
They are just building wider, flatter bases so they don't tip over.

21:46.600 --> 21:46.900
Yes.

21:47.500 --> 21:51.860
Over deep time, fragility is continually excluded by the sieve.

21:52.400 --> 21:54.080
Robustness simply persists.

21:54.480 --> 22:03.700
It mimics optimization beautifully, but it is just the natural mathematical consequence of the fact that robust closure is less likely to fall through the trapdoor.

22:03.700 --> 22:05.700
This is so paradigm shifting.

22:06.180 --> 22:09.240
In a weird, existential way, it takes the pressure off.

22:09.280 --> 22:09.720
I mean.

22:10.000 --> 22:21.000
Well, how often do you as a listener look at your own successful habits or a relationship that works and assume it had to be optimally designed from the start?

22:21.640 --> 22:27.560
We beat ourselves up trying to find the optimal morning routine, the optimal diet, the optimal career path.

22:28.100 --> 22:30.820
But maybe the universe doesn't care about optimal.

22:30.820 --> 22:34.940
Maybe you just need to find a sloppy loop that keeps you in the game.

22:35.400 --> 22:38.340
You just need mutual admissibility with your environment.

22:38.780 --> 22:43.440
That is a highly practical human translation of theorem 4.2 in the paper.

22:44.120 --> 22:45.720
Selection without optimization.

22:46.680 --> 22:51.940
The set of persistent structures contains absolutely no reference to an objective function.

22:52.940 --> 22:57.820
Any ranking we impose on ourselves or on biology is just that, an external imposition.

22:57.820 --> 23:04.780
Which perfectly bridges us into the next major pillar of this text, the projection of purpose.

23:04.940 --> 23:08.180
This is where things get really controversial in philosophical circles.

23:08.460 --> 23:15.220
Because if biology isn't actively optimizing toward a goal, what happens to the whole idea of purpose itself?

23:15.220 --> 23:28.040
If we zoom in from the evolution of an entire species down to the specific organs inside your body or the thoughts firing inside your brain, right now we use the language of purpose constantly.

23:28.440 --> 23:28.780
We do.

23:29.060 --> 23:31.720
We say the purpose of a heart is to pump blood.

23:32.140 --> 23:34.440
The purpose of a kidney is to filter waste.

23:34.800 --> 23:38.660
This is a massive concept in philosophy called functionalism, isn't it?

23:38.660 --> 23:40.400
It is the dominant paradigm.

23:40.920 --> 23:47.400
Functionalism is the idea that what a thing is, is entirely determined by what it does.

23:47.880 --> 23:50.140
Its causal role defines its existence.

23:50.860 --> 23:55.500
It's incredibly popular in both the philosophy of biology and the philosophy of mind.

23:55.740 --> 23:57.880
So it's all about the job it performs.

23:58.260 --> 24:02.320
A functionalist argues that it doesn't matter what a heart is made of.

24:02.320 --> 24:08.300
It could be made of biological meat, it could be made of 3D printed plastic, or it could be made of titanium.

24:08.820 --> 24:12.500
As long as it pumps blood through a system, it is a heart.

24:12.680 --> 24:13.480
It feels rigorous.

24:14.420 --> 24:17.500
It aligns perfectly with how human engineers talk.

24:17.880 --> 24:25.180
And it seems to escape the trap of optimization because it's just describing a system's current mechanical role.

24:25.440 --> 24:31.500
But if I'm tracking with Lickshin's logic, this paper is going to tear functionalism down to the studs too.

24:31.500 --> 24:32.340
Completely.

24:32.840 --> 24:40.600
Lickshin encounters the entire functionalist project with Proposition 6.1, the underdetermination of function by dynamics.

24:41.720 --> 24:42.280
Underdetermination.

24:42.640 --> 24:44.540
We throw that word around a lot in science.

24:44.680 --> 24:47.020
Break down exactly what it means in this context.

24:47.540 --> 24:56.240
It means that the pure physical dynamics of a system, the raw mathematical facts of how the particles move and interact,

24:57.020 --> 25:00.580
do not contain enough information to tell you what its function is.

25:00.580 --> 25:02.420
Let's look at your heart.

25:03.820 --> 25:11.480
Mathematically speaking, a persistent structure like a heart has an infinite number of invariant regularities.

25:11.920 --> 25:14.020
Regularities, like things it does consistently.

25:14.420 --> 25:14.680
Yes.

25:15.440 --> 25:17.620
Pumping blood is certainly one regularity.

25:18.160 --> 25:21.120
But the heart also produces rhythmic thumping sounds.

25:21.360 --> 25:24.320
It adds exactly a certain amount of mass to your chest cavity.

25:24.320 --> 25:27.960
It generates a highly specific measurable electromagnetic field.

25:28.180 --> 25:30.620
It produces a minor amount of thermal heat.

25:31.220 --> 25:37.380
From the objective perspective of the pure dynamical system, all of these regularities are completely equal.

25:37.880 --> 25:43.700
The closure condition, the loop that keeps you alive, preserves all of them simultaneously.

25:44.280 --> 25:49.580
The raw physics of the universe does not privilege the blood pumping over the sound making.

25:49.580 --> 25:51.560
But wait, let me push back here.

25:52.020 --> 25:54.360
If you cut out my heart, I die.

25:55.420 --> 25:58.640
The thumping sound isn't what keeps my brain oxygenated.

25:59.100 --> 26:02.580
The pumping of the blood is mechanically keeping me alive.

26:03.040 --> 26:05.600
How can you say they are dynamically equal?

26:05.940 --> 26:14.420
Because you are defining keeping you alive based on the coupled constraint of your specific environment and the rest of your body's architecture.

26:14.420 --> 26:18.040
Yes, if you remove the blood flow, the larger system fails.

26:18.640 --> 26:30.800
But if you were a predator that hunted by detecting the electromagnetic feel of a heartbeat, the electromagnetic regularity would be the dynamically relevant factor for your survival.

26:30.900 --> 26:31.540
Oh, I see.

26:31.860 --> 26:33.440
The heart doesn't know it's a blood pumper.

26:33.540 --> 26:39.260
The universe doesn't have a sticky note on the heart that says primary function, fluid dynamics.

26:39.820 --> 26:41.480
Look, she actually writes this brilliantly.

26:41.620 --> 26:42.960
Let me read this sentence from the text.

26:42.960 --> 26:52.800
To call a dynamical regularity a function is not to discover a fact about the system, but to impose a privileged coordinate frame upon it.

26:53.140 --> 26:53.500
Wow.

26:53.660 --> 26:54.440
Okay, I see it.

26:54.500 --> 26:57.000
It's like looking at constellations in the night sky.

26:57.540 --> 26:59.100
The stars are physically there.

26:59.720 --> 27:03.140
There are balls of burning gas persisting in a vacuum.

27:03.520 --> 27:07.620
Their relative positions to each other are invariant regularities.

27:07.960 --> 27:12.060
But the Big Dipper is not an intrinsic property of the universe.

27:12.260 --> 27:12.740
Exactly.

27:12.960 --> 27:24.380
The Big Dipper is a projection that human beings impose based on our highly specific vanish point on Earth and our cultural desire to see patterns in the noise.

27:24.380 --> 27:28.540
That analogy perfectly captures Flyxion's argument.

27:28.760 --> 27:37.800
To single out the blood pumping and declare the true function requires an observer to lay a privileged coordinate system over the raw behavior.

27:38.660 --> 27:40.880
It is an observer-imposed projection.

27:41.120 --> 27:49.040
And Flyxion uses this exact vulnerability to dismantle two major philosophical schools that try to save functionalism.

27:49.040 --> 27:49.960
Okay, let's hear them.

27:49.960 --> 27:51.280
Who are we debunking first?

27:51.460 --> 27:53.620
The first is teleological functionalism.

27:54.280 --> 28:03.380
Thinkers in this camp, like Wright and Neander, argue that we can solve the thumping sound versus plumping blood problem by looking at evolutionary history.

28:03.780 --> 28:05.800
Looking backwards to find purpose.

28:05.800 --> 28:06.720
Right.

28:06.720 --> 28:09.920
They say, sure, the heart does many things.

28:10.720 --> 28:18.140
But the reason it was selected for, in our ancestors, was because it pumped blood, not because it made noise.

28:18.760 --> 28:23.680
Therefore, pumping blood is its true biological proper function.

28:24.180 --> 28:26.500
It sounds like a solid argument.

28:26.720 --> 28:28.080
Does it get them out of the trap?

28:28.080 --> 28:34.520
It fails because it smuggles the illusion of optimization back in through the back door.

28:35.520 --> 28:41.700
Claiming a traits function is what it was selected for historically implies a retrospective, normative judgment.

28:41.700 --> 28:46.040
It assumes Mother Nature was tracking a gradient and aiming for a goal.

28:46.420 --> 28:51.820
But, as we established with our game show analogy, selection doesn't track gradients.

28:51.980 --> 28:54.500
It just excludes what falls through the trap door.

28:54.500 --> 29:05.100
In the ancestral environment, pumping blood, making a thumping sound, and having a certain mass were all bundled together in one organism that simply happened to survive.

29:05.320 --> 29:06.180
They all coveried.

29:06.300 --> 29:10.040
The sieve of selection didn't point a finger at the ancestor and say,

29:10.540 --> 29:13.700
I choose you specifically for your fluid dynamics.

29:14.060 --> 29:15.640
It just didn't kill the bundle.

29:16.180 --> 29:16.480
Ugh.

29:16.480 --> 29:26.860
So, picking the blood pumping as the historical reason is still just us, right now in the present, projecting our own engineering interests backward in time onto a blind process.

29:26.960 --> 29:27.520
Exactly.

29:27.680 --> 29:29.180
It's a retrospective projection.

29:29.420 --> 29:30.700
The universe still didn't care.

29:31.440 --> 29:37.560
And then, Flyxion goes after the second major school, computational functionalism.

29:37.620 --> 29:38.680
Okay, I know this one.

29:39.060 --> 29:45.640
This is huge in cognitive science, computer science, and the entire debate around artificial intelligence.

29:45.640 --> 29:47.960
With thinkers like Putnam and Fodor.

29:48.300 --> 29:48.820
Right.

29:49.260 --> 29:56.980
The idea here is that mental states, like having a thought or feeling pain, are defined purely by their computational role.

29:56.980 --> 30:00.200
The classic example is multiple realizability.

30:00.860 --> 30:10.620
A human brain made of wet, carbon-based neurons and a computer chip made of dry, silicon transistors can supposedly do the exact same computation.

30:10.620 --> 30:14.980
Therefore, the argument goes, they can possess the exact same mental state.

30:15.400 --> 30:20.600
They both can have a belief that it's raining outside because the functional output is identical.

30:21.180 --> 30:22.220
That is the core of it.

30:22.900 --> 30:27.980
Computational functionalism argues that function is about abstract equivalence classes.

30:28.680 --> 30:36.100
If two completely different physical states occupy the same causal role in a flow chart, they are functionally equivalent.

30:36.100 --> 30:47.820
But, Flyxion uses a dense mathematical concept called dynamical conjugacy, formalized in definition 8.1, to show why this is fundamentally flawed.

30:48.260 --> 30:49.740
Dynamical conjugacy.

30:50.620 --> 30:52.480
Okay, that sounds intense.

30:52.580 --> 30:54.240
Let's try to ELI-5 that.

30:54.680 --> 30:55.840
Explain it like I'm 5.

30:56.040 --> 31:01.820
Dynamical conjugacy is basically the rigorous mathematics of mapping one system onto another.

31:01.820 --> 31:09.400
If you want to say a human brain and a silicon AI chip are doing the same computation, you have to create a mathematical map.

31:09.520 --> 31:15.440
You have to draw lines connecting the physical states of the squishy brain to the physical states of the rigid chip.

31:15.660 --> 31:17.500
Making a one-to-one translation.

31:17.780 --> 31:26.220
But Proposition 8.2 in the text proves that for any persistent system, there are multiple, totally non-equivalent ways to draw those lines.

31:26.420 --> 31:28.560
So there isn't just one valid map.

31:28.780 --> 31:29.100
Right.

31:29.100 --> 31:45.880
You could map the silicon chip to the brain in a way that perfectly aligns their mathematical logic gates, but you could also, with equal mathematical validity, map them in a way that aligns their sheet dissipation over time.

31:46.320 --> 31:50.340
Or you could map them based on their electron mass distribution.

31:50.800 --> 31:56.760
And neither map is objectively the true one from the universe's perspective.

31:56.760 --> 31:58.520
Let's push an analogy here.

31:58.700 --> 32:10.580
It's like taking a map of New York City and a map of London and deciding they are functionally the same city because you chose to only map the geographic locations of Starbucks coffee shops.

32:10.720 --> 32:11.680
That's hilarious.

32:12.120 --> 32:12.960
But it makes sense.

32:13.180 --> 32:13.440
Yes.

32:13.580 --> 32:18.840
Under that specific, highly restrictive projection, they might look structurally equivalent.

32:19.660 --> 32:24.960
But if you chose to map the underground sewer pipes instead, they would look entirely different.

32:24.960 --> 32:30.120
That equivalence isn't an intrinsic, glowing property of the cities themselves.

32:30.480 --> 32:34.380
It's a direct result of your highly selective mapping choice.

32:34.640 --> 32:37.000
So wait, I want to pause here because this is getting heavy.

32:37.740 --> 32:40.980
Are you saying my brain doesn't actually process information?

32:41.740 --> 32:43.380
Are functions completely fake?

32:43.460 --> 32:45.740
Are we saying nothing actually does anything?

32:45.740 --> 32:51.420
No, and no, and this is a vital distinction to make so we don't fall into total absurdity.

32:51.900 --> 32:54.160
Flyxion is not an eliminativist.

32:54.940 --> 33:00.120
The paper isn't arguing that functions are hallucinations or that your heart doesn't pump blood.

33:00.480 --> 33:06.260
It is saying that functional descriptions are exactly like coordinate systems in physics.

33:06.480 --> 33:09.760
Like latitude and longitude lines on a globe.

33:09.760 --> 33:11.260
Exactly like that.

33:11.680 --> 33:17.340
Latitude and longitude are incredibly real, mathematically rigorous, and undeniably useful.

33:17.980 --> 33:22.560
You can use them to successfully navigate a cargo ship across the Pacific Ocean.

33:22.860 --> 33:25.200
They describe real physical geometry.

33:25.840 --> 33:32.780
But latitude and longitude lines do not exist as glowing red grids drawn on the physical dirt of the Earth.

33:32.860 --> 33:33.200
Right.

33:33.600 --> 33:36.500
They are a geometric projection made by an observer.

33:36.500 --> 33:42.740
Different observers say aliens visiting Earth could use an entirely different grid system

33:42.740 --> 33:48.340
based on magnetic poles or tidal forces, and both systems would be perfectly valid.

33:48.520 --> 33:52.380
So the function depends on the scale and the interest of whoever is looking.

33:52.800 --> 33:53.160
Yes.

33:53.920 --> 33:56.100
Look at a specific protein in your body.

33:57.120 --> 34:02.240
At the molecular level, an observer would say its function is its catalytic activity.

34:02.240 --> 34:08.920
Zoom out to the cellular level, and an observer says its function is part of a signaling pathway.

34:09.480 --> 34:14.240
Zoom out to the organism level, and the doctor says its function is maintaining homeostasis.

34:15.080 --> 34:16.140
And none of them are wrong.

34:16.560 --> 34:19.100
All of these coordinate systems are real.

34:19.400 --> 34:20.420
All of them are usable.

34:20.800 --> 34:25.280
But none of them is intrinsically the true primitive ontology of the universe.

34:25.280 --> 34:32.280
Functions are simply what an observer sees when they drape a coordinate system over a persistent structure.

34:32.400 --> 34:36.060
That is a massive, dizzying paradigm shift.

34:36.140 --> 34:36.340
Yeah.

34:36.500 --> 34:44.220
Because if functions, if the very purpose of a thing require an observer to project a coordinate system onto it,

34:44.620 --> 34:47.040
that forces us to turn the microscope around.

34:47.100 --> 34:47.460
It does.

34:47.460 --> 34:50.800
It forces us to ask, who exactly is the observer?

34:51.000 --> 34:54.220
Are we standing outside the universe drawing these lines?

34:54.380 --> 34:55.240
What are our limits?

34:55.240 --> 35:01.840
And that realization propels us into part three of the text, the embedded observer and structural blind spots.

35:02.320 --> 35:08.760
This is where the paper moves from biology into deep epistemology, the study of knowledge itself.

35:08.760 --> 35:15.000
The classic scientific ideal, and honestly the way most of us intuitively go through our daily lives,

35:15.800 --> 35:19.500
treats the observer as a god looking down on a chessboard.

35:19.660 --> 35:20.020
Yes.

35:20.640 --> 35:28.680
We think we are outside the system, objectively tallying up the pieces from a sterile, unconstrained vantage point.

35:28.840 --> 35:29.160
Right.

35:29.560 --> 35:37.740
It's the scientist in the pristine white coat, separated from the messy bacteria in the petri dish by a thick pane of glass.

35:37.740 --> 35:42.580
But Flyxion mathematically proves that this is a physical impossibility.

35:43.200 --> 35:44.580
The observer is not a god.

35:45.260 --> 35:50.140
The observer is a physical subsystem entirely inside the dynamical field.

35:50.460 --> 35:51.420
We are part of the mess.

35:51.840 --> 35:55.340
You are made of atoms, you are subject to the same laws of physics,

35:55.880 --> 36:01.440
and crucially, you are bound by the exact same closure conditions we talked about in biology.

36:01.760 --> 36:03.620
T of S must be a subset of S.

36:03.620 --> 36:04.100
Yes.

36:04.460 --> 36:10.720
Or, more specifically for an observer, T of Aux must be a subset of Aux.

36:10.960 --> 36:13.260
The observer must persist in order to observe.

36:13.460 --> 36:15.540
If you don't survive, you can't measure anything.

36:16.300 --> 36:19.660
And because the observer is just a small subset of the whole universe,

36:20.280 --> 36:24.960
their domain is necessarily mathematically smaller than the whole state space.

36:24.960 --> 36:29.000
Okay, so, we aren't the player moving the chess pieces.

36:29.640 --> 36:34.440
We are a pawn on the chess board, trying to understand the rules of the game,

36:34.640 --> 36:37.460
while simultaneously trying not to get captured.

36:37.640 --> 36:39.020
That's a great way to frame it.

36:39.420 --> 36:41.860
And because we are embedded inside the game,

36:42.420 --> 36:47.500
our observation is structurally limited by the rules of our own physical movement.

36:47.500 --> 36:53.900
Flyxion breaks down the geometry of observation into a few key mathematical concepts.

36:54.600 --> 36:58.920
And the first one is the reachable set, denoted mathematically as R.

36:59.480 --> 37:00.440
The reachable set.

37:00.820 --> 37:03.480
What does that actually mean for me, sitting here right now?

37:03.480 --> 37:09.000
It is the specific finite set of physical states that you, as an observer,

37:09.240 --> 37:14.300
can actually physically visit based on your initial conditions and constraints.

37:14.540 --> 37:15.480
The physical limits.

37:15.480 --> 37:18.300
Think about the physical reality of your existence.

37:18.540 --> 37:20.560
You were born in a specific year.

37:21.060 --> 37:23.460
You live on a specific rocky planet.

37:24.060 --> 37:28.100
You are equipped with a highly specific limited sensory apparatus.

37:28.780 --> 37:32.540
You can only see a tiny sliver of the electromagnetic spectrum.

37:33.040 --> 37:34.820
You can only move forward in time.

37:35.200 --> 37:36.180
My trajectory is locked.

37:36.720 --> 37:43.840
Your physical trajectory through the vast space of the universe is severely rigidly restricted.

37:43.840 --> 37:52.100
Therefore, there are parts of the universe, parts of the state space that you will simply never, ever reach.

37:52.460 --> 37:57.320
Not because you don't have a good enough telescope or because you haven't invented warp drive yet,

37:57.440 --> 38:02.480
but because your physical dynamics fundamentally do not intersect with them.

38:02.740 --> 38:03.780
I love this concept.

38:03.780 --> 38:07.520
It's like exploring a massive open world video game.

38:07.900 --> 38:16.780
You're playing this sprawling RPG and you open the map and there are huge sections of the continent that are completely grayed out in a fog of war.

38:16.920 --> 38:17.300
Right.

38:17.460 --> 38:19.320
But here is the terrifying kicker.

38:19.720 --> 38:23.720
They aren't grayed out because you haven't solved the puzzle to unlock them yet.

38:24.120 --> 38:30.220
They are grayed out because your character's base code physically prevents them from rendering there.

38:30.220 --> 38:35.060
The physics engine of your avatar simply does not allow access to that geometry.

38:35.620 --> 38:37.660
That is exactly what the reachable set is.

38:38.120 --> 38:45.580
Now combine that fog of war with the second concept, the observation map, which Flyxion denotes with the Greek letter pi.

38:45.940 --> 38:46.240
Pi.

38:46.640 --> 38:53.080
This concept deals with the fact that biological and mechanical observation is fundamentally lossy.

38:53.580 --> 38:57.360
It is a mathematical process called a non-injective mapping.

38:57.360 --> 39:02.160
Non-injective, let's translate that, lossy compression, like a blurry JPEG.

39:02.440 --> 39:03.440
Essentially, yes.

39:04.120 --> 39:14.120
In a non-injective map, multiple entirely distinct states of the real world can produce the exact same measurement on your instruments or on your retina.

39:14.260 --> 39:14.560
Right.

39:14.860 --> 39:26.260
Like how a gigantic, raging, supergent star millions of light years away looks exactly the same as a tiny little firefly buzzing right in front of my face on a dark night.

39:26.260 --> 39:27.420
Perfect example.

39:27.760 --> 39:31.840
Two totally different, wildly unequal states of physical reality.

39:32.600 --> 39:39.060
But the single photon hitting my eye creates the exact same visual measurement in my brain.

39:39.900 --> 39:40.860
A point of light.

39:41.020 --> 39:41.420
Precisely.

39:41.540 --> 39:47.860
In mathematical terms, the set of all the possible realities that could produce your specific measurement is called a fiber.

39:48.320 --> 39:51.960
So when you observe that point of light, you have a fiber of possible truths.

39:52.340 --> 39:55.780
It could be a star, it could be a firefly, it could be a laser pointer.

39:55.780 --> 40:00.060
But here is where the concept of the embedded observer changes everything.

40:00.680 --> 40:05.940
You don't actually have to guess among all possible realities in the universe.

40:05.940 --> 40:13.960
You only have to guess among the realities that exist inside your epistemically accessible fiber.

40:14.460 --> 40:15.000
Yes.

40:15.680 --> 40:17.360
Epistemically accessible fiber.

40:17.700 --> 40:22.980
That sounds like a horribly dry, high fiber cereal you buy at a health food store.

40:23.400 --> 40:24.360
Break down what that means.

40:24.360 --> 40:27.060
Epistemic just refers to knowledge.

40:27.280 --> 40:30.260
So this is the set of truths you can actually know.

40:30.700 --> 40:37.240
It is the mathematical intersection of what you measure the fiber and what is physically reachable for you, your reachable set.

40:37.440 --> 40:37.720
Okay.

40:37.900 --> 40:39.100
So where the two overlap.

40:39.100 --> 40:50.260
This intersection leads us to one of the most sobering conclusions in the paper, which Flyxion formalizes as theorem 11.2, the lifting problem.

40:50.440 --> 40:51.240
The lifting problem.

40:51.300 --> 40:53.080
Let me guess, this isn't about gym routines.

40:53.080 --> 40:53.900
No, no.

40:53.900 --> 41:04.320
When you make a measurement, you are trying to lift that localized observation up to correctly guess the true global state of the universe that caused it.

41:04.700 --> 41:12.680
But because you are permanently confined inside your reachable set, there are what the paper calls structurally unavailable explanations.

41:12.680 --> 41:26.880
There are absolute concrete truths about the universe, real physical states that would perfectly explain your observation that you can never, ever access.

41:26.880 --> 41:37.000
No matter how good your science gets, no matter how rigorous your logic is, you are structurally barred from them because your reachable set simply never intersects with them.

41:37.000 --> 41:44.240
So it's not just a matter of, we need to build a bigger particle accelerator or we need to launch a better space telescope.

41:44.500 --> 41:46.760
No, technology won't fix it.

41:46.820 --> 41:57.200
It's a fundamental mathematical law that our physical trajectory through the cosmos absolutely excludes certain truths from our reality.

41:57.640 --> 42:03.840
We are trying to solve a jigsaw puzzle where half the pieces don't just happen to be lost under the couch.

42:03.840 --> 42:07.280
They are mathematically forbidden from existing in our dimension.

42:08.600 --> 42:10.840
That is, well, honestly, it's terrifying.

42:11.160 --> 42:13.380
It induces a kind of epistemic vertigo.

42:13.640 --> 42:16.520
It is a profound structural underdetermination.

42:16.860 --> 42:20.560
It forces us to realize that our truth is bounded by our survival.

42:21.080 --> 42:26.300
But here's where it gets really interesting and where the math gives us a glimmer of hope.

42:26.300 --> 42:34.080
Let's move into the concept of epistemic curvature and what the paper calls the dark matter of truth.

42:34.840 --> 42:40.720
Because if there are truths that are structurally barred from us, are we just totally blind to them?

42:41.040 --> 42:44.720
Is it just a massive, impenetrable brick wall of ignorance?

42:45.060 --> 42:45.820
Not necessarily.

42:46.520 --> 42:51.140
And this is where Flyxion's geometry of the unseen becomes incredibly beautiful.

42:51.140 --> 42:56.240
The paper introduces the concept of inaccessible, persistent regions.

42:56.580 --> 42:58.480
Inaccessible, persistent regions.

42:58.700 --> 43:01.640
These are parts of the dynamical universe that exist.

43:01.860 --> 43:02.980
They are completely stable.

43:03.120 --> 43:04.540
They persist just like we do.

43:04.900 --> 43:10.860
But they will never, ever be observed by our specific class of biological observers.

43:11.260 --> 43:13.700
They are fully outside our reachable set.

43:14.040 --> 43:18.500
So there are invisible islands of reality floating out there in the state space.

43:18.500 --> 43:24.780
Entire dimensions or states of being that are stable, but utterly ghost-like to us.

43:25.140 --> 43:25.420
Yes.

43:26.100 --> 43:28.040
But, and this is theorem 13.3.

43:28.540 --> 43:34.000
Perhaps the most elegant theorem in the text your reachable set isn't just a random arbitrary shape.

43:34.720 --> 43:42.500
The boundary of what you can know is shaped by the exact same universal constraint field that defines those inaccessible regions.

43:42.860 --> 43:43.780
Shaped how?

43:43.780 --> 43:49.260
The boundary of your reachable set actually bends away from what you can't know.

43:49.720 --> 43:52.200
It bends away, like physical pressure.

43:52.660 --> 43:53.800
Mathematical pressure.

43:54.160 --> 43:56.320
Flyxion calls this epistemic curvature.

43:56.920 --> 44:02.000
The boundary of your knowledge is dented and deformed by the things you cannot see.

44:02.120 --> 44:07.980
Okay, my brain is starting to melt a little bit, trying to visualize a dented boundary of knowledge.

44:08.100 --> 44:08.600
Help me out.

44:08.600 --> 44:11.140
Let's use the author's own brilliant analogy.

44:12.020 --> 44:12.780
Dark matter.

44:13.720 --> 44:19.840
When astrophysicists look at a distant galaxy spinning in space, it is spinning way, way too fast.

44:20.440 --> 44:29.520
Based on all the visible light we can collect, the glowing stars, the gas clouds, the dust, there simply isn't enough physical mass to hold that galaxy together.

44:29.900 --> 44:34.480
Based on the gravity of what we can see, the galaxy should fly apart into the void.

44:34.660 --> 44:36.080
But it doesn't fly apart.

44:36.080 --> 44:43.760
Exactly. It stays together, which means there is an unfathomable amount of mass there that we cannot see.

44:44.100 --> 44:45.000
We call it dark matter.

44:45.200 --> 44:47.600
It does not interact with the electromagnetic spectrum.

44:48.140 --> 44:49.360
It doesn't absorb light.

44:49.460 --> 44:50.560
It doesn't reflect light.

44:50.960 --> 44:57.120
It is fundamentally physically residing in an inaccessible region of our observable states.

44:57.340 --> 44:59.560
But we absolutely know it is there.

44:59.880 --> 44:59.980
Why?

44:59.980 --> 45:03.500
Because of gravity. Gravitational lensing.

45:04.000 --> 45:11.120
Even if we can't see the dark matter, it has so much mass that it warps the fabric of space-time around it.

45:11.200 --> 45:13.960
It bends the light of the stars we can see.

45:14.100 --> 45:15.200
That is it. Exactly.

45:15.440 --> 45:17.320
It deforms the visible universe.

45:17.700 --> 45:22.020
We detect the unseen by measuring the geometric anomalies of the seen.

45:22.020 --> 45:30.040
Flyxion takes this profound concept from astrophysics and applies it directly to epistemology, to the theomy of knowledge itself.

45:30.260 --> 45:30.580
Wow.

45:31.080 --> 45:35.160
Epistemological dark matter lies just beyond the boundary of our reachable set.

45:35.700 --> 45:44.840
We can't see the truth itself, but we can mathematically detect its presence by measuring what Flyxion calls the Hessian matrix of our own observable constraints.

45:44.840 --> 45:49.120
Okay, Hessian matrix. You're throwing some heavy calculus terms at me. What is that?

